  &lt;p id="MdkYT0"&gt;When the Mac Mini was first introduced in early 2005, it was pitched as a compact “stripped-down” desktop — and the most affordable Mac in Apple’s lineup. Steve Jobs referred to it as &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GJpZGeihy0s"&gt;a “BYODKM” system&lt;/a&gt;: you’d bring your own display, keyboard, and mouse, and the Mini would provide a dependable computing experience with all the benefits of macOS. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="wRW1ff"&gt;The Mac Mini has carried on ever since. There have been periods where the Mini has been sidelined and ignored by Apple for long stretches of time. But the debut of Apple Silicon &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/11/17/21570046/apple-mac-mini-2020-m1-review"&gt;gave it a new lease on life&lt;/a&gt;. Even if the overall design didn’t change much in the transition from Intel to Apple’s in-house chips, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/23566070/apple-mac-mini-m2-pro-2023-review"&gt;the Mini’s potential soared&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
